<div id="content" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<strong><a href="./OndrejSterbak">OndrejSterbak</a></strong>: I was recently thinking about rings in games generally. Do anybody know why there are only 2 ring slots when we have 10 fingers? <img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/smile.png" alt=":)" height="15" width="15">  <p>
Is it the idea that the magic power of the ring would diminish the power of the other rings near it or what? 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./NerdanelVampire">NerdanelVampire</a>: In the real world you can even wear more than one ring per finger. The ToME situation's clear purpose is to balance out the rings' great potential power. I think it comes from D&amp;D. The explanation was that the rings interfered with other rings in the same hand. (Incidentally, I wonder why you can't wear a very large number of rings of nothing. Aren't they magicless? Or is it that they are magical but in an entirely useless way?) 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a></strong>: Rings tend to be some of the most powerful artifacts around, so various phony explanations for one-ring-per-hand had to be come pu with, heh. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./FeathinSilyar">FeathinSilyar</a></strong>:  Mm, five Rings of Speed on one hand, five Rings of Extra Attacks on the other...Okay fine I'll ditch one of each so I can have Vilya and Flare. 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./NerdanelVampire">NerdanelVampire</a>: My mother has an engagement ring, a wedding ring, and an anniversary ring all on the same finger. Ten rings is far from the real maximum. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./KermitCrill">KermitCrill</a></strong>: D&amp;D might have this rule, and I know the majority of old roguelikes all stuck to it.  I don't know what the official explanation might be, but maybe they only come in one size, and won't fit on your other fingers.  <img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/smile.png" alt=":)" height="15" width="15"> 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./JohnGilmore">JohnGilmore</a></strong>: Actually, I think that there's an assumption that all magic rings can change sizes somewhere in there too. Otherwise, a ring sized for a half-ogre would fit a hobbit at all. In fact, probably only about 1/3 of the rings that where found would be wearable by any given character. The only one necklace thing is staight balance though. In real life, we have mister T, after all. 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./DarkGod">DarkGod</a>: Your mother's rings are not powerful magical instruments of mayhem(are they ?) <img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/smile.png" alt=":)" height="15" width="15"> 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./KermitCrill">KermitCrill</a></strong>: *pictures a ToME mage wearing three rings on each finger*...  "Your covered hands feel unsuitable for spellcasting."  :P 
</p>
